TY  - JOUR
AU  - Rothschild, Casey
AU  - Scheuer, Florian
T1  - Redistributive Taxation in the Roy Model*
PY  - 2013
Y1  - 2013/05/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/qjs076
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 128
IS  - 2
SP  - 623
EP  - 668
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - We consider optimal redistribution in a model where individuals can self-select into one of several possible sectors based on heterogeneity in a multidimensional skill vector. We first show that when the government does not observe the sectoral choice or underlying skills of its citizens, the constrained Pareto frontier can be implemented with a single nonlinear income tax. We then characterize this optimal tax schedule. If sectoral inputs are complements, a many-sector model with self-selection leads to optimal income taxes that are less progressive than the corresponding taxes in a standard single-sector model under natural conditions. However, they are more progressive than in canonical multisector economies with discrete types and without occupational choice or overlapping sectoral wage distributions. 
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qjs076
ER  - 



